column1: Will the FAO Food Price Index for April 2022 reach or exceed 150.0?
column6: ['Open']
Time update and it looks like 157. To date

Given that the index averaged 159.3 points in March, it seems likely that the April price will exceed 150. Conflict in Ukraine pushed the price of wheat higher in March, and it seems likely that that will continue to put upward pressure on prices into April.
It has come at 159 on April 7th release. Of the components - oil is likely to be high as Indonesia banned exports, Cerreal will continue to remain high due to Ukraine war

March reference is already above this level primarily due to concerns over wheat exports from Russia and Ukraine, while higher fertilizer prices could negatively impact the level of technology used on most crops and should affect the world's SnD. Protective measures from some governments should also help sustain a higher reference.
Time update

Russia-Ukraine war is putting pressure on the wheat market, which in turn is driving demand for other agricultural commodities. Fertilizers (from Russia and Belarus) not making it to farms is also affecting cereal and grain agricultural commodities.
With pressure on grains etc, I think it will be above 150
Wheat prices soaring, trending higher, seems like all food input prices trading higher through April as well. Highly likely to see the index price in >150.

Based on current grain prices, I wrote on March 19 that, "I think the March FFPI value will likely be somewhere in the range of 147.0-150.5." Based on that analysis, I forecast that it was 100% certain that April would see the index >= 150.0. However, my estimate for March was clearly too conservative. From today's press release: "The FAO Food Price Index* (FFPI) averaged 159.3 points in March 2022, up 17.9 points (12.6 percent) from February." That April's index value will be >= 150.0 is all but assured, as cash and futures prices remain extremely high in grain, oilseed, palm oil, meat, dairy, sugar and fertilizer markets.
March numbers in:
March index now reported at 159.3, up 17.9 points (!!!) m-o-m. Hard to see the world getting back to normal “baseline” conditions in 23 days. All in.

"The FFPI averaged 140.7 points in February 2022, up 5.3 points from January and as much as 24.1 points above its level a year ago -- a new all-time high, exceeding the previous top of February 2011 by 3.1 points. The February rise was led by large increases in vegetable oil and dairy price sub-indices. Cereals and meat prices were also up, while the sugar price sub-index fell for the third consecutive month" Have we seen the worst of it yet, or is April too soon to see the worst of it this year? If the index continues to rise at current levels for March (numbers release on April 8), then April, then it can easily reach 150.0 but given that the index it's already at its all time high by 3.1 pts, one would imagine strong measures are being taken to control prices. Supply issues are being addressed, weather has affected crops in major producers like Canada, Brazil, and the pandemic is relatively under control, but war in Ukraine is not showing signs or easing. Brent oil went below $100 for the first time today since Russia invaded Ukraine in late February, as uncertainty that the euro zone will be able to effectively sanction Russian energy exports eases and huge release of oil from emergency reserves are announced. Lockdowns in China, where over 23 cities and 100 million people remain on lockdown because of Covid19 outbreak are expected to slow oil demand. Could be that impact of rise in oil prices has already been priced in for March and would easy in April. Let's see what March numbers show. https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/

In working on this question (https://app.datacamp.com/workspace/w/9cef92f2-009c-4572-b17e-b5db07bea220) - and I'm not finished yet, so I'll come back and update later - I think the FAO Food Price Index will go up by 10 points over the next 12 months. outside view: historic one year increase =6% growth (calculated from excel (https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/) april 2021: 122.1*1.06=129.42 base case answer: probably not let's try with recent numbers average monthly increase (from jan 2021 till feb 2022) = 2% pred_april = 140.7*1.02^2 = 145.23 monthly sd = 2% 150-145.23 = 4.77 percentage points 2 times 1 sd higher > (1-.84)^2 = 2.56% this is an underestimation given recent developments (ukraine) we could take february's value as the average 2 times at least average increase = 0.5^2=25% It takes some time to increase prices, so let's say next months increase is 5% and the other one 6% (on average) (half an sd) probability 0.67(=0.5+0.17)*0.84(=0.5+0.34) = 56.3% that is around the middle, let's artificially increase to 60% to be able to say: probably yes

The outside view would probably suggest no, based on the base rate of the measure never having exceeded 150 before. The dataset shows the largest 2 month gain since 1990 was 14.2, in the summer of 2020. The average gain since 1990 is 0.5 and the median is 0.2. I think this is a case where the outside view isn't that useful. The index would have to gain 9.3 points over the next two months to exceed, and the invasion of Ukraine kicked off in February, so the latest February number won't include the effects of that, and the impacts to wheat and other crops are expected to be high. So I think it's likely to exceed.

Trending substantially upwards to record levels which were recorded pre the impact of the war in Ukraine, this global shortage seems to suggest it would continue rising steeply since the last closing prices.
Just repeating my forecast to post this: https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/20/world/americas/ukraine-war-global-food-crisis.html

The monthly changes are positively autocorrelated and with big rises recently more big rises are likely. I got a 25% chance of a 2 month change of 6.6% contingent on the preceding month being up more than 3.5%. Without the contingency the chance of a move that large was 6.5%. So generally moves this big are rare but in the current environment not that uncommon.

Wheat spot prices have climbed 25% since the war began (spiked even higher than that, but has since come down), and I assume cereals are some substantial % of the FAO food price index (but not sure what % goes to wheat -- the other cereals haven't climbed as much, other than corn at +15%).

I was at 95%, but realistically, there's <0.5% chance the FFPI will be below 150.0 in April. The index went up 5.3 points to 140.7 in Feb, based on data largely before the invasion of Ukraine. Since Feb 28, wheat prices spiked up ~40% higher than closing prices on Feb 28 and have since fallen to ~20% higher than Feb 28 close prices. Feb 28 close prices were already substantially higher than the previous year's prices and higher than everything since early 2011. The last time wheat prices were this high was in the first half of 2008, when there were riots all over the world because so many people couldn't afford food. Oilseed prices have also gone up: canola is at an all-time high, and soybeans are near all-time highs and above last month's average. Sunflower jumped on news of the invasion and may be coming down to a higher level. Palm oil jumped on news of the invasion but appears to have come down, possibly to resume its upward trend. On top of that, fertilizer prices are still at all-time highs, and climbing. Corn prices jumped after the invasion, are about 15% higher than Feb 28 closing prices and are not that far from all-time highs. Rice prices continue to climb. And the pandemic dislocations that had brought the index into the 130's are all still relevant. If the index climbed 5.3 points in Feb, I don't see how it won't climb substantially more in March. Increases could slow in April, but I don't see how all of this could be reversed enough to bring the index under 150 in April.

I have done a bit more work on this and I think my initial thoughts were off. Dropping substantially.

Asked, any commodities trader will show high concern for this event. In poorer countries, where price moves are harder to be hampered by govs etc., strong increases can be observed already. Should the Ukraine-Russia war last some more weeks, we could reach a territory where the harvest, essential to global food markets might not be produced in time. Ukraine's president, Zelenky recently urged farmes to seed even in the face of war to stabilize the GDP. This shows the significance of the conflict. Instabilities and global inflation threaten these price levels, why I think they are likely to appear.

3/17: All signs are pointing to increasing food prices: several severe droughts, increase in fuel/fertilizer/wheat prices due to Russia war on Ukraine, poor crop expectations in China (wheat). So the question is whether we've seen all of this priced in already or not. I don't think we have since the war that is triggering several of these only started in late February. So it is probable that we see a similar, if not higher increase rate in March and a more mild increase by the time April data is available.

In the not too distant future given the roll of Ukraine in food production I expect this increase. Just a matter of whether this impact can manifest by April or a lag in the indicator prevents it by April.
9.3 index points to go with 2 releases, so need 4.6 increase in both months. Feb 22 increase was 5.2 so this is possible.

The Index hit 140.1 in February, so hitting target would require an increase of 7% over two months. Looking at the historic data on the FAO site going back to 1990, there have been 17 two-month periods with that minimum increase (17 out of 384 period, or 4.4%), with 39 periods jumping 5% or more (10% of total). So, jump is rare, but not unheard of.

When oil prices increase so does food with the high at 140.7 and oil decreasing in price and the world has adjusted to the war in Ukraine I don’t believe it will reach 150.0 in the time frame of the question. Since posting no new data …

Further driving this likelihood higher is the historical data in question largely was not directly related to massive sanctions on one of the top energy and foodstuff suppliers in the world. Further, in this previous instance the areas of kinetic war did not include major energy/foodstuff countries directly.

The index was up 5.3 points before Russia invaded Ukraine. Grain and oilseed prices have gone up steeply since then because of Russia's invasion of Ukraine, as both countries are heavy exporters of grains (e.g., 25% of world wheat exports) and also oilseeds (#6 and #7 for oilseed exports in the world). The index is already at 140.7 for Feb. It will be up sharply in March, possibly even over 150.0 then. April could be worse, and it probably won't be better.

As of writing this forecast the latest FAO Food Price Index was 140.7 as per the February reading. This is a new all time high for the index, with prices being on a drastic rise since 2020. This most recent rise can mainly be attributed to supply shocks caused by the ongoing conflict in Ukraine(Cereal -- ie Wheat & Vegetable Oil -- ie sunflower oil), issue with the South American Soy harvest (Vegetable Oil -- ie Soy Oil), and decreased Palm Oil Exports from Indonesia (Vegetable Oil). Putting immense upward pressure on the price of Cereal and Vegetable Oil components of the Index.
